{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600611/1930090601/0204.xml":{"full_text":"HENRY FORO SEES\n1 DEPRESSION\u2019S END\n(Ascribes Prosperity to Peo\nple Substituting \u201cThinking\u201d\nfor Speculating.\nth# Associated. Press.\nNEW YORK, September 6. -Sailing\naboard the liner Bremen for a six weeks\u2019\nbusiness and pleasure trip in Europe,\nHenry Ford predicted an early end to\nthe present business depression.\nHe said the depression might out last\nClctober, but that business now was bet\nter than two years ago. He. ascribed\nthe growing prosperity to the people\n\u2022\u00fcbstltuting \u2018\u2018thinking\u2019\u2019 for speculating.\nHe said he would combine business\nand pleasure on his trip and he, Mrs.\nFord and the party of three who were\naccompanying them, would motor\nthrough France and Germany, stopping\nat the Ford factory at Cologne. The\nothers in the party were Mr. and Mrs.\nCharles A. Hodges of Detroit and E. G.\nLiebold, his secretary.\nThe party had boarded the North\n\u00a9erman liner by a lower gangplank and\nthe fact that Mr. Ford intended to sail\nwas not disclosed to newspaper men until\nafter he was aboard. He then received\nthem in his suite.\nAsked his opinion on politics and pro\nhibition, he said no politics existed in\nAmerica today and that prohibition was\nhere to stay. \"Except for a damp spot\nhere and there,\u201d he said, \"America is\ndrv.\u201d\nQuestioned as to the truth of reports\nthat the Ford Co. planned the manufac\nture of six-cylinder cars, he said:\n\u201cI've got more important news for\nyou than that. I\u2019m building a hotel.\u201d\n\u201cWhat for?\u201d he was asked\n\u201cFor rumors,\u201d he said, spelling out the\nlast word.\nSEVEN ARMY OFFICERS\nPROMOTED TO COLONELS\nSherburne, Ryan, Campbell, Lonp,\nMitchell, Dengler and Williams\nto Fill Vacancies.\nBe ven officers of the Army have been\npromoted to the grade of colonel to\nfill vacancies. They are Lieut. Col.\nThomas L. Sherburne. Cavalry, at Fort\nHuachuca, Ariz.: Lieut. Col. Lewis S.\nRyan, Field Artillery, at Cincinnati;\nLieut. Col. Tilman Campbell, Finance\nDepartment, at Fort Sam Houston,\nTex., and Lieut.. Col. James L. Long, at\nFort Mason, Calif.; Lieut. Col. Ralph\nM. Mitchell, at Harrisburg, Pa.; Lieut.\nCol. Frederick L. Dengler. at San Fran\ncisco. and Lieut. Col, Richard H. Wil\nliams, at Ridgewood, N. J., all of the\nCoast Artillery\nLieut. Col. Joseph F. Barnes, Field\nArtillery, in the Panama Canal Zone,\nwill be placed on the retired list De\ncember 31, on his own application, after\nmore than 33 years\u2019 service; Col. Fran\ncis W. Griffin, Field Artillery, at Big\nIsland, Va, on leave, has been trans\nferred to the retired list on account of\ndisability incident to the service: Maj.\nLeo G. Heffernan, Air Corps, has been\ntransferred from Rantoul. 111., to the\nPanama Canal Zone; Maj. John D.\nTownsend, Infantry, from San Juan,\nPorto Rico, to Pittsburgh, Pa.; Maj.\nCharles B. Kendall, Medical Corps,\nfrom Fort Eustis, Va., to the Walter\nReed General Hospital, this city; Capt.\nHaskell Allison, Signal Corps, from\nHarrisburg, Pa., to Baltimore, Md.;\nCapt. John J. Gorman. Infantry, from\nFort Snelling. Minn., to the Oklahoma\nAgricultural College at Stillwater; Capt.\nGeorge W. Dunn, jr, Coast Artillery,\nfrom Fort Hancock, N. J.. to the Mis\nsissippi Agricultural College, and First\nLieut. Alan A. Whittaker, jr.. Coast\nArtillery, in the Philippines, has been\nordered to his home in the United\nStates for retirement.\nTRIP MAY CLEAR KILLING\nOF 8-YEAR-OLD GIRL\nSouth Bend Policemen Obtain\n\u201cValuable Information\u201d in Ap\npel Case in Tennessee.\nBt the Associat ed Press.\nSOUTH BEND. Ind.. September\nTwo South Bend policemen returned\nyesterday from Gallatin, Tenn, with\nwhat they declared was \u201cvaluable in\nfrmation\u201d which ultimately may lead to\nthe arrest of the person who attacked\nand murdered 8-year-old Marverine\nAppel here more than a week ago.\n\u201cWe now have something to work\nupon.\u201d said David C. Raymond, police\ncaptain.\nThe policemen were sent to Gallatin,\nwhere the murdered girl's body was\ntaken for burial by the mother. Mrs.\nEulia Appel, after a \u201ctip\u201d that valuable\ninformation could be obtained in the\nTennessee City.\nOtis Appel, 12, and Comer Appel, 10,\nbrothers of the dead girl, who also went\nto Gallatin, wpre understood to have\nbeen questioned.\nA new theory was advanced concern\ning the murd-r. It, was understood po\nlice were proceeding on the ground\nthat the girl might have been attacked\nand killed by youthful playmates.\nThree men, arrested here yesterday,\nwere released today after being ques\ntioned.\nDEPUTY SHERIFF KILLED\nIN RAID ON LIQUOR STILL\nAlleged Moonshiner Wounded in\nGunplay\u2014Slayer Object of\nWidespread Hunt,\nBr Mi* Asocial *d Pre*\u00bb.\nCAIRO. 111, September 6 Deputy\nSheriff Herbert. Coryell of Sandusky,\nnear here, was shot and killed and Wil\nliam Bryant, alleged moonshiner, was\nwounded in the leg, in a shooting dur\ning a raid on a whisky still in a wooded\nsection near Sandusky last night.\nIn a dying statement Coryell named\nMinus Dunning, about SO. a timberman\nand alleged notorious bootlegger, as his\nslayer. Dunning was the object, of a\nwidespread man hunt in Southern Illi\nnois yesterday. Bryant is in a hospital\nher*.\nojjEFORE making your\nplans for the Fall and\nWinter look into thi\u00ab\nSPECIAL OFFER at the\nj. Blackstone Hotel\n1916 17th St. Diet. 3516\nHandsomely furnished\nroom, with private bath\u2014\nand breakfast in the case\neach morning. For two, by\nthe month, each at the spe\ncial rate of\n$8.50 per Week!\nThe Blaekstooa is a new\nand modern hotel \u2014eonven-\nx iently located to everywhere\nA downtown, saving car fare.\nT Harry Wood, Mgr.\n1\nSSSSS\u2014\u2014\u2014 tmmmmmmmmmmmmmmnmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm i_\n\n'Woodward Lothrop\niO TH ll XKI F and G Streets\nOnly 6 More Days to Save in The Semi-A